===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|hiden|lang=enm}}, {{term|huden|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|hydan|hȳdan|to hide, conceal, preserve|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|hūdijanan|to conceal|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|(s)keudh-|to cover, wrap, encase|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|(s)keu-|to cover|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nds|-}} (''ver''){{term|hüden|lang=nds}}, (''ver''){{term|hüen||to hide, cover, conceal|lang=nds}}, Welsh {{term|cuddio||to hide|lang=cy}}, Ancient Greek {{term|||tr=keúthein|to conceal|lang=grc}}, Sanskrit {{term|||tr=kuharam|a cave|lang=sa}}. Related to {{l|en|hut}} and {{l|en|sky}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|hides|hiding|hid|hidden}}

# {{transitive}} To put (something) in a place where it will be harder to [[discover]] or [[out of sight]].
#: ''He '''hides''' his magazines under the bed.''
#: ''The politicians were accused of keeping information '''hidden''' from the public.''
#* '''1856''', {{w|Gustave Flaubert}}, {{w|Madame Bovary}}, Part III Chapter XI, translated by Eleanor Marx-Aveling
#*: The blind man, whom he had not been able to cure with the pomade, had gone back to the hill of Bois-Guillaume, where he told the travellers of the vain attempt of the druggist, to such an extent, that Homais when he went to town '''hid''' himself behind the curtains of the "Hirondelle" to avoid meeting him.
# {{intransitive}} To put oneself in a place where one will be harder to find or out of sight.

